definition.value: A HODE that consists of (10E,12Z)-octadecadienoic acid with the hydroxy substituent located at position 9.
A DiHOME obtained by formal dihydroxylation of the 9,10-double bond of octadeca-9,12-dienoic acid (the 12Z-geoisomer).
A DiHOME obtained by formal dihydroxylation of the 12,13-double bond of octadeca-9,12-dienoic acid (the 9Z-geoisomer).
An O-acylcarnitine having oleoyl as the acyl substituent.
An acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the acyl group contains twenty-two carbons with six double bonds and is attached to the glycero moiety at either position 1 or 2.
An acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl group contains fifteen carbons with no double bonds and is attached to the glycero moiety at either position 1 or 2.

An  lysophosphatidylcholine in which the acyl group contains seventeen carbons and no double bonds. If R1 is an acyl group and R2 is a hydrogen then the molecule is a 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolaminecholine. If R1 is a hydrogen and R2 is an acyl group then the molecule is a 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine.
An O-acylcarnitine having 3-hydroxybutyryl as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having isobutyryl as the acyl substituent.
An N-acylglycine that is glycine with an amine hydrogen substituted by a 2-methylbut-2-enoyl (tiglyl) group.
An O-acylcarnitine having acetyl as the acyl substituent.
A C5-acylcarnitine having isovaleryl as the acyl substituent.
A C5-acylcarnitine having 2-methylbutyryl as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having succinyl as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having glutaryl as the acyl substituent.
An O-decenoylcarnitine having (4Z)-decenoyl as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having palmitoyl (hexadecanoyl) as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having linoleoyl as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having stearoyl (octadecanoyl) as the acyl substituent.

A member of the class of triazoles that is butan-2-ol which is substituted at positions 2, 3, and 4 by phenyl, 1H-1,2,4-triazol-1-yl and p-chlorophenyl groups, respectively. An inhibitor of brassinosteroid biosynthesis.

Any of a class of phosphosphingolipids in which the amino group of a sphingoid base is in amide linkage with one of several fatty acids, while the terminal hydroxy group of the sphingoid base is esterified to phosphorylethanolamine.
A dipeptide composed of glycine and L-tyrosine joined by a peptide linkage.
A dipeptide formed from L-leucine and L-serine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-leucine and L-phenylalanine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-methionine and L-alanine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-phenylalanine and glycine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-valine and glycine residues.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the gamma-carboxy group of glutamic acid with the amino group of another glutamic acid.
A dipeptide obtained by formal condensation of the gamma-carboxy group of glutamic acid with the amino group of glutamine
A fatty amide obtained by the formal condensation of (11Z)-eicosaenoic acid with ethanolamine.
A dipeptide formed from L-alanyl and L-leucine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-arginine and L-phenylalanine residues. It exhibits vasorelaxant activity.
A  lysophosphatidylcholine P-16:0 in which the alk-1-enyl group is hexadec-1-en-1-yl.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 18:0 in which the acyl substituent is located at position 1 and is specified as stearoyl.
A dipeptide formed from glycine and L-tryptophan residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-histidine and L-alanine residues.
A 2-monoglyceride where the acyl group is (9Z)-octadecenoyl.
A phosphatidylcholine 32:1 in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 are hexadecanoyl and (9Z)-hexadec-9-enoyl respectively.
A dipeptide formed from L-histidine and L-valine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-isoleucine and glycine residues.
A nucleoside analogue that is allopurinol with a beta-D-ribofuranosyl moiety at the 1-position.

An S-hydrocarbyl-L-cysteine that is L-cysteine in which the  hydrogen attached to the sulphur is replaced by a prop-2-enyl group. It commonly occurs in garlic and has been found to exhibit antineoplastic activity.
A cholesterol ester in which the acyl group contains 22 carbons in total and 6 double bonds.
A dipeptide formed from L-isoleucine and L-valine residues.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 22:5 in which the acyl group at position 1 is (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z)-docosapentaenoyl and the hydroxy group at position 2 is unsubstituted.
A member of the class of formamides  having a N-methyl substituent.
A dipeptide formed from L-leucine and L-glutamic acid residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-leucine and glycine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-lysine and L-leucine residues.
A  N-acetyl-L-amino acid that is the N-acetyl derivative of L-tryptophan.
